                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d873">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.003/9–644: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-09-06T13:00:00+07:00"
                            >September 6, 1944—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received September 6—12:18 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1513. I saw Foreign Minister yesterday, reurtel 1163, September 1. He stated that
                    as areas concerned are still in Jap hands no action has been taken but he sees
                    no reason why provisions of articles II and III of treaty cannot be implemented
                    satisfactorily when Diplomatic Quarter and Settlements are taken over. He
                    inquired what particularly Department had in mind in making its inquiry.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
